00:01:15.330 --> 00:01:19.830
Throughout much of the twentieth century, there have been bold predictions

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:24.979
about new technologies or systems that would “revolutionise” education.

00:01:26.279 --> 00:01:33.319
The invention and mass production of TVs was heralded as the start of a new educational revolution,

00:01:33.659 --> 00:01:40.639
where anyone, anywhere, could get access to the best possible teaching, right there on their screen.

00:01:41.339 --> 00:01:48.309
In the 1960s there was a lot of talk about the idea of a teaching machine, with which students

00:01:48.309 --> 00:01:54.649
could learn at their own pace and get personalised feedback from a specially programmed computer.

00:01:55.529 --> 00:02:01.229
Then there were correspondence courses, where people would receive new materials–textbooks,

00:02:01.539 --> 00:02:08.389
videos and audio lectures–every week or fortnight, and they could learn at their own pace.

00:02:09.239 --> 00:02:15.789
There were new designs of schools, new ideas about learning styles, increased use of IQ testing.

00:02:16.949 --> 00:02:23.579
And with the mass-adoption of computers and later the Internet, many people believed that this would

00:02:23.589 --> 00:02:30.859
be the real game-changer, allowing anyone, anywhere to access a modern-day library of Alexandria.

00:02:31.969 --> 00:02:38.129
And then came the MOOCs, the massive open online courses, where you could follow a Harvard

00:02:38.129 --> 00:02:43.307
course on philosophy and then take a computer science course at the University of Oxford.

00:02:44.487 --> 00:02:48.917
There was virtual reality, which was trumpeted as yet another tool that

00:02:48.917 --> 00:02:53.727
would revolutionise education and have us all learning in the metaverse.

00:02:55.567 --> 00:02:59.532
None of these, I think it is perfectly fair to say, have had

00:02:59.532 --> 00:03:03.487
the revolutionary impact that many people thought they would.

00:03:04.777 --> 00:03:12.357
We humans are awful at predicting the future, and the future of education is clearly no exception.

00:03:13.497 --> 00:03:18.187
So, with that in mind, let’s talk about some of the most prominent

00:03:18.217 --> 00:03:22.867
ideas today about what education will look like in the future.

